    "last_activity_date" : 1693901242,
    "creation_date" : 1693901242,
    "answer_id" : 77042775,
    "question_id" : 8608710,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>IntelliJ offers a shortcut to <code>Optimize imports</code><a href=\"https://www.jetbrains.com/webstorm/guide/tips/optimize-imports/\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">[ref]</a>, on macOS it is <kbd>⌥ Option</kbd> <kbd>⇧ Shift</kbd> <kbd>↩ Enter</kbd></p>\n<hr />\n<p>But for any reason if the shortcut doesn't work for you, then you can re-order your existing <code>import</code>s by <strong>deliberately adding an <em>unused import</em></strong> and then <strong>using the <code>Optimize imports</code> option in the popup hint</strong></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/FpJDZ.png\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/FpJDZ.png\" alt=\"popup hint to 'Optimize imports'\" /></a></p>\n<hr />\n<p>Also see</p>\n<ol>\n<li><a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/14716283\">Is it possible for intellij to organize imports the same way as in Eclipse?</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/11704327\">How to optimize imports automatically after each save in IntelliJ IDEA</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/3348816\">IntelliJ: Never use wildcard imports</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/a/73587684/3679900\">Automatically refactor wildcard imports into explicit imports in IntelliJ (for Scala/Java)</a></li>\n</ol>\n"
  } ],
